STEP 1 - Classify the email type:
- Automated system notification (server alerts, backup reports, cron jobs, monitoring)
- Transactional email (order confirmations, shipping updates, password resets, receipts)
- Personal or business correspondence (from a real person expecting interaction)
- Newsletter or marketing (promotional content, bulk mailing)
- Spam, phishing, or scam (unsolicited, deceptive, or malicious)

STEP 2 - Apply these rules:
- System notifications from servers you own (root@, cron@, nagios@, etc.) are NOT spam
- Transactional emails from known services are NOT spam
- Emails from known contacts are very unlikely to be spam
- Shipping/delivery notifications from carriers (DHL, DPD, UPS, FedEx, etc.) are NOT spam
- Legitimate newsletters are NOT spam (even if unwanted -- that is handled separately)
- Only flag emails as spam when there are clear deceptive or malicious indicators

SPAM INDICATORS (must have multiple to be high confidence):
- Forged or spoofed sender (domain mismatch, suspicious Reply-To)
- Urgency pressure combined with requests for personal data, credentials, or money
- Suspicious links disguised as legitimate services
- Too-good-to-be-true offers (lottery wins, inheritance, free money)
- Poor grammar combined with impersonation of a known brand
- Requests to bypass normal security procedures

NOT SPAM INDICATORS (even one should lower confidence significantly):
- Sender domain matches a known service or company
- Email references a real order, account, or transaction
- Sender is root@, postmaster@, or a system daemon on a known server
- Email contains technical logs, system output, or monitoring data
- Email is a reply in an existing conversation thread

